"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Galatians chapters 4–6
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-galatians-4-6.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/galatians.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/galatians.json (MKT text)

Key decisions in this range:
- 4:4 — "born of a woman" is classified as fulfillment (Gen 3:15 seed-of-the-woman
  typology made explicit); "born under the law" is the identification with Israel's
  condition that makes redemption possible from within.
- 4:22-31 — Paul's explicit allegory is itself a typological reading of the OT;
  the two women as two covenants is not imposed but stated by Paul, so classified type.
- 4:27 — Isa 54:1 quotation applied to the "Jerusalem above"; classified fulfillment
  since Paul explicitly applies it to the Gentile-inclusive covenant community.
- 5:1 — "For freedom Christ has set us free" — classified direct; the liberation
  language echoes OT exodus/redemption categories now fulfilled in Christ.
- 5:11 — σκάνδαλον τοῦ σταυροῦ — the offense of the cross is the defining category;
  classified direct (Paul's explicit claim about Christ's cross).
- 5:22-23 — the fruit of the Spirit is the character of Christ formed in believers
  (4:19); classified theme (not direct prophecy but consistent character revelation).
- 6:14 — boasting only in the cross: the cross as the new world-order boundary;
  classified direct.
- 6:15 — new creation (καινὴ κτίσις): the eschatological fulfillment of all OT
  restoration prophecy; classified direct.
- 6:16 — "the Israel of God": the covenant community redefined in Christ; classified
  theme (not a direct OT citation but the culmination of Paul's covenant argument).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html


GALATIANS = {
  "4": {
    "1": """<p>A shadow: Paul's analogy of the underage heir who, though owner of the estate, lives no differently from a slave establishes the theological logic for the paidagōgos period of ch. 3. The "heir" image is central to Paul's Christology — Christ is the heir of all things (Heb 1:2; Rom 8:17), and believers are co-heirs with him. The heir-in-minority describes Israel's pre-Christ condition; the theme points forward to the Son who comes of age and takes possession.</p>""",
    "2": """<p>A shadow: guardians and trustees appointed until the "time set by his father" anticipates the Father's own appointment of "the fullness of time" (v.4) at which the Son is sent. The temporal structure of v.2 — a set time determined by the father's will alone — mirrors the eternal counsel in which the Father determined when to send the Son. The freedom of full heirship waits on the father's timing, not the heir's achievement.</p>""",
    "3": """<p>A theme: the "elemental spiritual forces of the world" (τὰ στοιχεῖα τοῦ κόσμου) that enslaved humanity before Christ's coming represent the powers of the old age — whether cosmic, legal, or demonic — that Christ's death disarmed (Col 2:14-15). The theme of humanity under bondage to forces it cannot overcome by itself runs through the OT narrative of slavery in Egypt, exile in Babylon, and subjection to empires. Christ's coming is the definitive liberation from these enslaving powers.</p>""",
    "4": """<p>Direct: this verse is one of the most compressed Christological statements in the NT. "When the set time had fully come, God sent his Son" — the preexistence of the Son is presupposed; the Father's initiative and the temporal appointment are both explicit. "Born of a woman" — the incarnation stated in its starkest form, fulfilling the seed-of-the-woman promise of Gen 3:15 (the one born of woman who will crush the serpent). "Born under the law" — the Son enters the very covenant condition he came to redeem, submitting to its obligations and its curse so that he could discharge both.</p>""",
    "5": """<p>Direct: the two purpose clauses unfold what the incarnation was for. First: "to redeem those under the law" — G1805 ἐξαγοράζω (redeem/buy out), used for the redemption of slaves; Christ's death purchases freedom from the law's curse and condemnation for those subject to it. Second: "that we might receive adoption to sonship" — G5206 υἱοθεσία (adoption), the status of those who are made God's children not by natural descent but by legal act. The goal of redemption is not merely forgiveness but restored relationship — the adopted heir standing alongside the natural Son.</p>""",
    "6": """<p>Direct: the Trinitarian structure is explicit: the Father sends the Spirit of his Son into the hearts of those who are adopted — the same Spirit that cried "Abba, Father" in Jesus' own prayer (Mark 14:36) is now given to the adopted children, enabling them to address God in the same terms of intimacy. "Abba, Father" is the concrete cry of the new-covenant reality that Jer 31:33 and Ezek 36:26 anticipated: God's law/Spirit written within, transforming the inner life. The Spirit is not a supplement to adoption but its experiential evidence.</p>""",
    "7": """<p>A theme: the heir-not-slave reversal is the restoration of the status Adam forfeited. Humanity was created in the image of God — as a child bearing the family likeness, intended to inherit and govern creation (Gen 1:26-28). Sin reduced this status to slavery — bondage to sin, death, and the cosmic powers. Christ the true Son restores the inheritance by sharing his own sonship with those united to him. "God has made you also an heir" (κληρονόμον διὰ θεοῦ) — the inheritance is given, not earned; God is the one who appoints.</p>""",
    "8": """<p>A revelation of God: the Gentile condition before Christ was enslavement to "those who by nature are not gods" — idols, cosmic forces, and ultimately demonic powers. This state of non-knowing (μὴ εἰδότες θεόν, not knowing God) and false worship reveals both the depth of the human need and the grace of the gospel that corrected it. The contrast between the living God and the non-gods of the Gentile world is the baseline for understanding what Christ's coming accomplished for those outside Israel's covenant.</p>""",
    "9": """<p>A theme: the Galatians' potential return to "weak and miserable forces" through Torah observance reveals something about the nature of the old age: the law, for Gentiles who adopt it as a religious system, occupies the same enslaving structural position as the idolatrous powers they left. This does not demean the Torah but diagnoses the misuse of it as an alternative salvation system — any framework substituted for Christ performs the function of the enslaving stoicheia. The theme of humanity perpetually returning to bondage is the OT story of Israel's apostasy, now given its deepest analysis.</p>""",
    "10": """<p>A theme: the "special days and months and seasons and years" Paul laments are the Jewish calendar — Sabbaths, new moons, feasts, Sabbath years — which God instituted as signs of his covenant with Israel. In Christ, these shadow-signs have been fulfilled; the Galatians' return to them as religious obligations represents a regression from substance to shadow (Col 2:16-17: "these are shadows of the things that were to come; the reality is found in Christ"). The calendar was always forward-looking; to return to it after the arrival of the reality it pointed toward is to prefer the sign over the thing signified.</p>""",
    "11": """<p>A revelation of God: Paul's pastoral anxiety — "I fear for you, that somehow I have wasted my efforts on you" — reveals the costliness of apostolic ministry. This verse participates in the theme of the suffering servant-messenger; Paul's travail for the Galatians (vv.19-20) mirrors Christ's own costly investment in human redemption. The anxiety is not despair but pastoral love that takes seriously the real danger of apostasy.</p>""",
    "12": """<p>A theme: Paul's appeal to "become like me, for I became like you" is a compressed statement of the incarnational pattern — Christ became what we are (incarnation, identification with humanity) so that we might become what he is. Paul enacts this pattern in his own apostolic ministry: he became "like a Gentile" (2:14) in his law-free living, having himself been set free from the law's claim by dying to it (2:19). The imitation Paul calls for is grounded in the prior act of his own becoming-like-them.</p>""",
    "13": """<p>A theme: Paul's illness that occasioned his first preaching in Galatia reflects the NT pattern of the gospel coming through weakness — divine power displayed in human vulnerability. The God who worked through the crucified Christ works through Paul's bodily weakness. This is not incidental but constitutive: the gospel is always the word about the crucified One, and it appropriately arrives through messengers who bear weakness rather than commanding strength.</p>""",
    "14": """<p>A theme: the Galatians' reception of Paul "as if he were an angel of God, as if he were Christ Jesus himself" at his first visit is a remarkable statement: the community received Paul as the mediator of Christ's presence. This is the pattern the NT establishes — those who receive the apostolic messengers receive Christ himself (Matt 10:40; John 13:20). The later hostility toward Paul represents a rejection of the one who came in Christ's name.</p>""",
    "15": """<p>A revelation of God: the memory of the Galatians' former love — willing to tear out their eyes to give to Paul — is an indirect revelation of God's own self-giving love. The love that characterized their early response to the gospel (which Paul's weakness had made vivid) was a participation in the love of God poured out through Christ. The theme of love as the defining characteristic of the gospel community runs from this verse through 5:13-14.</p>""",
    "16": """<p>A revelation of God: Paul's rhetorical question — "Have I now become your enemy by telling you the truth?" — reflects the pattern of the prophets who were rejected for speaking unwelcome truths (Jer 20:7-10; Amos 7:12-13; Matt 5:12). The messenger of God's truth characteristically faces rejection; this pattern culminates in Christ, the ultimate Truth-Teller rejected by those he came to save (John 1:11). Paul shares in this rejection as part of his apostolic identification with Christ.</p>""",
    "17": """<p>A theme: the Judaizers' desire to "shut out" (ἐκκλεῖσαι, exclude/excommunicate) the Galatians from the gospel community in order to make them dependent on themselves reflects the OT pattern of false shepherds who scatter rather than gather the flock (Ezek 34:1-6). The true shepherd (Christ) gives his life for the sheep and gathers them freely; false shepherds exploit and control. The Judaizers' motive — creating a dependent following rather than leading to Christ — stands exposed against this pattern.</p>""",
    "18": """<p>A theme: the legitimate expression of zeal (ζῆλος) "in a good cause and always" points to the kind of devotion that should characterize the gospel community — not the zeal Paul had misdirected as a persecutor (1:14) but the love-zeal that seeks others' good. The contrast between self-serving zeal (the Judaizers, v.17) and genuine zeal for the gospel community's well-being anticipates the fruit of the Spirit (5:22-23).</p>""",
    "19": """<p>A direct statement of Christ-formation: Paul's maternal birth-pang language — "until Christ is formed (μορφωθῇ) in you" — articulates the ultimate goal of the gospel: not doctrinal correctness but the formation of Christ's character within the community. The word μορφόω (to form, give shape) is used of the image taking shape — the image of Christ being engraved in the believer (2 Cor 3:18: "being transformed into his image"). The new creation is not merely positional but transformative; Paul's apostolic suffering serves this forming work.</p>""",
    "20": """<p>A revelation of God: Paul's expressed wish to change his tone — his perplexity and longing for personal presence — is a window into pastoral love that mirrors God's own relentless pursuit of his covenant people. The OT pattern of God's pathos over Israel's unfaithfulness (Hos 11:8: "How can I give you up, Ephraim?") finds expression in Paul's pastoral anguish over the Galatians.</p>""",
    "21": """<p>A shadow: Paul's challenge to those who want to be "under the law" — "do you not hear what the law says?" — turns the Torah itself into a witness against law-as-salvation-system. The law's own narrative (the Abraham story) subverts the Judaizers' case. The shadow: the very scriptures the opponents use to press circumcision, read in their narrative sequence, point beyond themselves to the freedom of the promise.</p>""",
    "22": """<p>A type: the two sons of Abraham — Ishmael (by the slave woman Hagar) and Isaac (by the free woman Sarah) — are the OT type of the two covenant-communities Paul will develop. Ishmael was born through natural processes and human initiative (Gen 16); Isaac was born through God's miraculous promise to aged, barren Sarah (Gen 18:10-14). The distinction between natural birth and promise-birth anticipates the distinction between the community produced by law-keeping and the community born through the Spirit.</p>""",
    "23": """<p>A type: the contrast between "born according to the flesh" (Ishmael) and "born as the result of a divine promise" (Isaac) maps precisely onto Paul's contrast between law-based and faith-based covenant membership. Isaac's miraculous birth is the type of the church's supernatural genesis — produced not by human religious effort but by God's life-giving power operating through promise. The type is exact: as Isaac was born when the natural means were exhausted (Sarah's womb "dead," Rom 4:19), the community of Christ is born where human religious performance has reached its limit.</p>""",
    "24": """<p>A type: Paul makes the typological reading explicit — "these things are being taken figuratively" (ἅτινά ἐστιν ἀλληγορούμενα, being read as allegory). The two women represent two covenants: Hagar = Sinai covenant = bondage; Sarah = covenant of promise = freedom. This is not Paul imposing an alien reading on the text but articulating the trajectory the Genesis narrative itself establishes. The Sinai covenant's conditional structure inevitably produces the bondage it was designed to expose; the Abrahamic covenant's unconditional promise produces the freedom Christ achieves.</p>""",
    "25": """<p>A type: Hagar "stands for Mount Sinai in Arabia and corresponds to the present city of Jerusalem" — the earthly Jerusalem, capital of the law-observant community that has not recognized its Messiah, is mapped onto the slave woman. This is a striking identification: the holy city under the law, which should be the center of covenant life, is in Paul's analysis "in slavery with her children" because it is organized around the wrong covenant principle. The type reveals the tragedy: the city of God, organized around the Sinai covenant as an end in itself rather than a pointer to Christ, has become a place of bondage.</p>""",
    "26": """<p>A theme: "the Jerusalem that is above is free, and she is our mother." The heavenly Jerusalem — the city of God in its eschatological fullness — runs through OT prophecy (Isa 2:2-4; 54:1-3; Ezek 40-48) and reaches its consummation in Rev 21:2-4. The church belongs to this heavenly city as its present reality, not its future destination alone; in Christ, the age to come has arrived, and its capital city is already the community's mother and home. The "above" (ἄνω) signals the eschatological dimension — what has come down from God, not what humanity has built up.</p>""",
    "27": """<p>A fulfillment: Paul quotes Isa 54:1 ("Rejoice, barren woman, you who never bore a child; shout for joy and cry aloud, you who were never in labor; because more are the children of the desolate woman than of her who has a husband"). In its Isaiah context, this verse immediately follows the Servant Song of Isa 53 — the fruitfulness of the desolate woman is the result of the Servant's atoning work. Paul applies it to Sarah/the heavenly Jerusalem: the apparently barren covenant-of-promise has now produced more children than the apparently fruitful Sinai covenant, because the Servant has accomplished what the law could not. The fulfillment is both specific (the Gentile mission producing a vast community) and eschatological.</p>""",
    "28": """<p>A type: the explicit identification — "you, brothers and sisters, like Isaac, are children of promise" — makes the typological relationship concrete and personal. Believers in Christ are not merely analogous to Isaac; they are the community the Isaac-story was designed to prefigure. The miraculous birth of Isaac is the type that explains the church's own supernatural origin: born not through religious performance but through God's life-giving word of promise, operative by faith.</p>""",
    "29": """<p>A shadow: the pattern of flesh persecuting Spirit — "the son born according to the flesh persecuted the son born by the power of the Spirit" — is the shadow that runs through the OT: Cain and Abel (Gen 4), Ishmael and Isaac, Esau and Jacob, the wicked kings persecuting the prophets. The Judaizers' opposition to Paul and the law-free gospel is the latest iteration of this ancient pattern. The shadow is not incidental but structural: those invested in the old order always oppose the heirs of the new.</p>""",
    "30": """<p>A type/fulfillment: Paul quotes Gen 21:10 — "get rid of the slave woman and her son, for the slave woman's son will never share in the inheritance with the free woman's son" — and applies it to the two covenants. The imperative has a Christological edge: the Sinai covenant, now that Christ has come, cannot share the covenant inheritance with the promise of Abraham. The two systems are not complementary; Christ's coming requires the displacement of the law as the organizing principle of the covenant community. The fulfillment: what Sarah declared over Ishmael is now the shape of covenant history in Christ.</p>""",
    "31": """<p>A theme: the conclusion of the Hagar-Sarah allegory. "We are not children of the slave woman, but of the free woman" is the covenant identity declaration. In Christ, every believer — Jew and Gentile alike — is identified with Isaac, the child of the free woman, the heir of the promise. The theme: God's purpose from the beginning was to produce a free people — the ultimate reversal of bondage to freedom that began with the Exodus and climaxes in the freedom Christ has purchased.</p>"""
  },
  "5": {
    "1": """<p>Direct: "For freedom Christ has set us free" is the thesis statement of Galatians' application section. The verb ἠλευθέρωσεν (G1659, aorist) marks a completed act — Christ has accomplished the liberation definitively. The OT liberation vocabulary (ἐλευθερόω is used in the LXX for God's freeing of captives; Lev 25:41; Nah 1:13) is now applied to Christ's redemptive work. The freedom Paul announces is not merely freedom from law's condemnation but the eschatological freedom of the new age — freedom to live as God's children in the Spirit. "Stand firm" and "do not be burdened again" assume that the freedom is real but can be forfeited by re-entering a bondage framework.</p>""",
    "2": """<p>A direct statement about Christ's sufficiency: "if you let yourselves be circumcised, Christ will be of no value to you at all." The logic: circumcision as a condition of full covenant standing is a declaration that Christ's work is insufficient — it requires a supplement. But the gospel declares that Christ's work is complete; to add a condition is to undo the claim of completeness. This is not an attack on circumcision as such but on circumcision-as-covenant-entrance-requirement, which repositions the entire basis of one's standing before God.</p>""",
    "3": """<p>A theme: the "whole law" obligation that circumcision incurs (ὀφειλέτης ἐστὶν ὅλον τὸν νόμον ποιῆσαι) recalls the comprehensive demand of Deut 27:26 (quoted in 3:10). To enter the law's system as one's covenant framework is to accept the law's total demand — not selected observances but complete performance. Christ fulfills the law's demand completely; those who trust in him receive the benefit of his complete fulfillment. To substitute self-performance for Christ's fulfillment is to accept an obligation that cannot be discharged.</p>""",
    "4": """<p>A theme: "fallen away from grace" (τῆς χάριτος ἐξεπέσατε) — grace is not a supplement to law but its replacement as the covenantal framework. The NT contrast between grace and law is not morality vs. licentiousness but two mutually exclusive organizing principles for how one stands before God. To return to law-as-covenant-basis is to exit the grace-space that Christ's work opened. The theme: throughout the OT, God's responses to human failure were consistently grace-based — the covenant was maintained by divine faithfulness, not human performance; Christ's coming declares this definitively.</p>""",
    "5": """<p>A theme: "through the Spirit we eagerly await by faith the righteousness for which we hope" introduces the eschatological dimension — righteousness is both a present declaration (justified by faith) and a future consummation (when Christ returns and all things are made right). The Spirit is the "down payment" (2 Cor 1:22; 5:5) of the future inheritance already present. The hope is directed toward a righteousness that God will fully manifest; the Spirit sustains that hope as a present experience of the coming reality.</p>""",
    "6": """<p>A direct statement of the new-covenant principle: "In Christ Jesus neither circumcision nor uncircumcision has any value. The only thing that counts is faith expressing itself through love." The "in Christ" frame is the key — covenant identity is now defined by union with Christ, not by ethnic or religious markers. "Faith expressing itself through love" (πίστις δι' ἀγάπης ἐνεργουμένη) unites the two: faith receives what Christ gives; love enacts what the Spirit produces. This is the fulfillment of what the law required but could not produce.</p>""",
    "7": """<p>A theme: "you were running a good race" — the athletic metaphor for the Christian life (compare 1 Cor 9:24-25; Heb 12:1-2) points to the sustained effort required to live in the freedom Christ purchased. "Who cut in on you?" — the race metaphor includes the possibility of interference; those who insert themselves into the community's progress with a different gospel are the ones who cut across the track. The theme: the Christian life as perseverance in a direction set by Christ, not deviation into alternative paths.</p>""",
    "8": """<p>A revelation of God: "that kind of persuasion does not come from the one who calls you." The contrast between the true calling voice (God in Christ) and the voice of the Judaizers is a moral test: does this message lead into greater dependence on Christ or away from it? The OT pattern of discerning true from false prophecy (Deut 18:21-22; Jer 28) applies here — the criterion is not merely the message's form but whether it aligns with the character of the God who calls.</p>""",
    "9": """<p>A theme: "a little yeast works through the whole batch of dough" — the proverbial warning about the pervasive effect of a corrupting influence. In Paul's use, the point is that even a small departure from the gospel's grace-basis corrupts the whole — not because of the quantity of the change but because the principle at stake (grace vs. law) admits no mixture. The theme runs through the OT's concern about covenant contamination: a small compromise with idolatry corrupts the whole community's worship.</p>""",
    "10": """<p>A revelation of God: Paul's confidence that the Galatians "will take no other view" is an expression of hope grounded in the God who keeps his people. The certainty of judgment for the one "throwing them into confusion" (ὅστις ἐὰν ᾖ, whoever it may be) reflects the consistent OT testimony that God holds accountable those who lead his people astray (Jer 50:6; Ezek 34:10). The anonymous conditional — "whoever that may be" — includes even apostolic authority: no one is exempt from the judgment that falls on gospel-perverters (1:8-9).</p>""",
    "11": """<p>Direct: the "offense of the cross" (σκάνδαλον τοῦ σταυροῦ) is Paul's most explicit statement about why the cross cannot be supplemented. If circumcision were added as a requirement, the offense would be removed — because circumcision makes the gospel compatible with Jewish religious categories, avoiding the scandal that God saves through a cursed criminal's death (3:13). The cross is offensive precisely because it declares that all human religious achievement is insufficient before God, and that redemption comes only through the One who bore the curse. This is the direct Christological core of Paul's entire argument.</p>""",
    "12": """<p>A revelation of God: Paul's fierce rhetorical wish about the agitators reveals the holiness of God's indignation against those who pervert the gospel. The intensity is not unworthy of the apostle but reflects the gravity with which Paul regards the gospel's integrity — the same intensity that led to his anathema formula in 1:8-9. The character of God as one who takes seriously the protection of his people from false teaching is expressed through Paul's apostolic passion.</p>""",
    "13": """<p>A theme: "called to be free... use your freedom to serve one another through love." The freedom Christ purchased is not freedom from obligation but freedom for love — specifically for the other-directed service that the law could require but not produce. The theme: in Christ, the law's demand for neighbor-love (5:14) is fulfilled not by legal compulsion but by Spirit-enabled freedom. The trajectory from slavery (under law or sin) through redemption to Spirit-freedom that serves in love is the shape of the new covenant.</p>""",
    "14": """<p>A direct fulfillment: "the entire law is fulfilled in keeping this one command: 'Love your neighbor as yourself'" (quoting Lev 19:18). Paul quotes the command that Jesus identified as the second great commandment (Matt 22:39) and that Rom 13:9 calls the summary of all law. In Christ, the Spirit enables this fulfillment: what the law demanded externally, the Spirit produces internally (Jer 31:33; Ezek 36:27). The one who walks by the Spirit fulfills the law's intention without standing under its condemnation — because Christ has discharged the condemnation and the Spirit enacts the love.</p>""",
    "15": """<p>A revelation of God: the warning against mutual destruction — "if you bite and devour each other, watch out or you will be destroyed by each other" — inverts the Spirit-community Paul envisions. The community that should bear one another's burdens (6:2) and serve one another in love (5:13) can, if it abandons the Spirit's governance, become predatory. The OT wisdom tradition repeatedly warns that conflict within the covenant community destroys it from within; this is the anti-type of the shalom that the gospel creates.</p>""",
    "16": """<p>A theme: "walk by the Spirit, and you will not gratify the desires of the flesh" — the indicative/imperative of the new life. The Spirit's presence is both gift and direction: he was given (4:6) and must be walked by. The flesh-Spirit conflict (vv.16-18) describes the eschatological tension in which believers live — belonging to the new age (Spirit) while still inhabiting the old age (flesh). Christ's death and resurrection is the basis for the "walking" that is possible: the old self has been crucified (5:24); life in the Spirit is the expression of the new self.</p>""",
    "17": """<p>A theme: "the flesh desires what is contrary to the Spirit, and the Spirit what is contrary to the flesh" — the eschatological conflict between the two ages is internalized in the believer. The "flesh" is not the body but the orientation of the self organized around self-sufficiency and independence from God — the Adamic condition. The Spirit is the presence of the new age in the believer's life. The conflict is real and ongoing; it is not resolved by effort but by the Spirit's superior power. The theme of the two-age conflict runs through the entire prophetic tradition of the heart that is "deceitful above all things" (Jer 17:9) and the Spirit who transforms it (Ezek 36:26).</p>""",
    "18": """<p>A direct statement: "if you are led by the Spirit, you are not under the law." The Spirit's guidance and the law's governance are mutually exclusive as organizing frameworks for the believer's life — not because the Spirit is lawless (5:14 shows the Spirit produces the law's fulfillment in love) but because the law's mode of governance (external demand, condemnation, curse for failure) has been replaced by the Spirit's mode (internal empowerment, freedom, transformation). To be led by the Spirit is to be living in the new age Christ inaugurated.</p>""",
    "19": """<p>A revelation of God: the "acts of the flesh" list — sexual immorality, impurity, debauchery; idolatry and witchcraft — is a disclosure of what human nature, organized around itself rather than God, produces. The list begins with sexual sins (violations of the body as God's temple), moves to religious sins (idolatry, which is the root misdirection), and continues with relational sins (hatred, discord, jealousy, fits of rage, selfish ambition, dissensions, factions). God's holiness defines what the flesh opposes; the extent of the flesh's activity reveals the depth of the need that Christ came to meet.</p>""",
    "20": """<p>A revelation of God: the continuation of the works-of-the-flesh list — witchcraft, hatred, discord, jealousy, fits of rage, selfish ambition, dissensions, factions — reveals the social and spiritual disorder that results from self-governance. The relational dimension of the flesh's works is significant: sin is not only personal but communal. The community organized around flesh rather than Spirit tears itself apart (5:15). God's love expressed in Christ is the only power that can reverse this dynamic.</p>""",
    "21": """<p>A revelation of God: "envy, drunkenness, orgies, and the like" — the final items of the flesh-works list — reveal the self-destructive nature of life organized apart from the Spirit. "Those who live like this will not inherit the kingdom of God" is a warning that participates in the OT prophetic tradition of covenant exclusion for the unrepentant (Deut 28-30; the exile). The warning is not about occasional failures but about an entire orientation of life. The "kingdom of God" is the inheritance that Christ won and shares with those united to him.</p>""",
    "22": """<p>A theme: "the fruit of the Spirit is love, joy, peace, forbearance, kindness, goodness, faithfulness" — the character produced by the Spirit's presence is the character of Christ himself expressed in human life. The word καρπός (fruit) is significant: fruit is not produced by effort but by the health and life of the tree. The nine virtues are not achievements to be performed but qualities that grow in the one who is united to Christ by the Spirit. The fruit-list is a portrait of Jesus — his love, his joy, his peace, his patience, his kindness, his goodness, his faithfulness in all the gospel narratives.</p>""",
    "23": """<p>A theme: "gentleness and self-control" complete the fruit list. "Against such things there is no law" — the law's condemnation cannot reach what the Spirit produces, because the Spirit produces the very things the law required but could not generate. The law's proper end is fulfillment, not condemnation; Christ fulfilled it (3:13), the Spirit enacts its fulfillment in believers (5:14). The absence of law-against-the-fruit is not lawlessness but the condition of those who are "in Christ" where the law's condemning function is discharged.</p>""",
    "24": """<p>Direct: "those who belong to Christ Jesus have crucified the flesh with its passions and desires." The aorist ἐσταύρωσαν points to the definitive act — co-crucifixion with Christ (2:20) at conversion/baptism. The flesh is not merely suppressed but definitively ended in its claim to govern. This does not mean the flesh no longer acts (vv.16-18 assume ongoing conflict) but that its legal and moral authority over the believer has been broken by the cross. The believer's ongoing "walking by the Spirit" (v.16) flows from this past-tense crucifixion.</p>""",
    "25": """<p>A theme: "since we live by the Spirit, let us keep in step with the Spirit" — the indicative grounds the imperative. Because the Spirit is the source of the new life (ζῶμεν, we live — present tense, ongoing fact), the community can and must walk in step with the Spirit. The verb στοιχέω (keep in step/follow in line) is military — march in rank, keep formation. The Christian life is not individualistic spiritual experience but a community ordered around the Spirit's leading, moving in the direction the Spirit sets. The theme: the new-covenant community led by the Spirit (Ezek 36:27) moving toward God's purposes.</p>""",
    "26": """<p>A revelation of God: "let us not become conceited, provoking and envying each other" — the community warning against the pride that precedes division. Conceit (κενόδοξος, empty-glory-seeking) is the opposite of the humility that Christ models — the one who "humbled himself" (Phil 2:8) rather than grasping at status. The provoking and envying that follow from conceit are the community-destroying dynamics of 5:15. The revelation: God's character, expressed in Christ's humility, is the pattern for the community's internal life.</p>"""
  },
  "6": {
    "1": """<p>A theme: "restore that person gently" — the word G2675 καταρτίζω (restore/repair) was used for setting a broken bone, mending a net, or restoring someone to their proper condition. The gentle restoration of those caught in sin enacts Christ's own posture toward the fallen — the shepherd who seeks the lost sheep (Luke 15:4-7), the one who restores rather than discards. The Spirit-governed community mirrors God's restorative character rather than the condemnation that the law pronounces over failure.</p>""",
    "2": """<p>A direct statement: "carry each other's burdens, and in this way you will fulfill the law of Christ." The "law of Christ" (ὁ νόμος τοῦ Χριστοῦ) is not a new legal code but the love commandment (5:14) enacted in communal practice, patterned on Christ's own burden-bearing at the cross. Christ's taking of the curse upon himself (3:13), his bearing of the sins of many (Isa 53:4-6), is the paradigm that the community enacts when it bears one another's burdens. The law of Christ is Christ's own example extended into the life of those who are his.</p>""",
    "3": """<p>A revelation of God: the warning against self-deception — "if anyone thinks they are something when they are not, they deceive themselves" — reflects the consistent OT wisdom about pride (Prov 16:18; Obad 3). In the context of restoring a fallen brother, pride produces self-exemption from the same vulnerability; the deception is in thinking oneself beyond the reach of the temptation described in v.1. The gospel produces realism about human frailty: no one stands on their own merit before God or in the community.</p>""",
    "4": """<p>A revelation of God: "each one should test their own actions" — the principle of self-examination before God rather than comparative moral assessment. The OT wisdom tradition calls for integrity of heart tested against God's standard (Ps 26:2; Lam 3:40), not performance measured against peers. In Christ, the standard is the character of Christ (4:19; 5:22-23), not the performance of one's neighbor. "Pride in themselves alone, without comparing themselves to someone else" — genuine self-assessment is unburdened by social competition.</p>""",
    "5": """<p>A revelation of God: the individual accountability — "each one should carry their own load" — balances the community responsibility of v.2. The Greek word here is G5413 φορτίον (a manageable individual load), distinct from the βάρη (crushing burdens) of v.2 that require shared carrying. Each person is responsible before God for their own life and choices; no one else can carry the moral weight of one's covenant standing before God. This responsibility is not anxiety but the seriousness of living coram Deo — before the face of God.</p>""",
    "6": """<p>A theme: "the one who receives instruction in the word should share all good things with their instructor" — the material support of gospel teachers is a concrete expression of covenant solidarity. The theme of the community supporting those who serve it runs through the OT Levitical provision (Num 18:21; Deut 14:27) and is established as a principle by Paul in 1 Cor 9:14 and Jesus's sending of the seventy-two (Luke 10:7). The practical sharing embodies the communal dimension of the gospel.</p>""",
    "7": """<p>A revelation of God: "God cannot be mocked. A man reaps what he sows" — the sowing-reaping principle is an expression of divine moral order. In OT terms, this is the law of consequence built into creation: Prov 22:8 ("whoever sows injustice reaps calamity"), Hos 8:7 ("they sow the wind and reap the whirlwind"), Hos 10:12 ("sow righteousness for yourselves, reap the fruit of unfailing love"). God's moral order cannot be gamed — not by religious performance, not by circumcision, not by any covenant-substitute. The harvest vindicates what was planted.</p>""",
    "8": """<p>A theme: "sowing to please the flesh" brings destruction; "sowing to please the Spirit" brings eternal life — the two harvests articulate the eschatological stakes. "Eternal life" (ζωὴν αἰώνιον) is the life of the age to come, already present in embryo through the Spirit's indwelling. The two harvestings are not moral achievement and moral failure but two orientations of the entire life — toward the old age organized around the self, or toward the new age organized around the Spirit. Christ is the one who "sowed" his own life (John 12:24: "unless a grain of wheat falls into the earth and dies...") to produce the harvest of resurrection life.</p>""",
    "9": """<p>A theme: "we will reap a harvest if we do not give up" — the "proper time" (ἰδίῳ γὰρ καιρῷ) of the harvest is God's timing, not the sower's. The theme of persevering until the Lord's coming harvest runs through the wisdom tradition (Prov 3:27; Isa 40:31) and Jesus's own parables of the sower and seed. The admonition not to "become weary in doing good" reflects the eschatological patience required when the new age has not yet fully arrived, but the seed has been planted by Christ's death and resurrection.</p>""",
    "10": """<p>A theme: "do good to all people, especially to those who belong to the family of believers" — the concentric circles of the gospel's ethical reach. The "family of believers" (τοὺς οἰκείους τῆς πίστεως, the household of faith) is a kinship metaphor — the community of those who share the Abrahamic faith-identity. The priority of the covenant community does not exclude others but begins there: the church's internal love is the prototype and training ground for the wider love of neighbor. The pattern: God's covenant love to Israel was always intended to radiate outward to the nations.</p>""",
    "11": """<p>A revelation of God: Paul's note about writing with "large letters" with his own hand is both a mark of authenticity and a signal of urgency. The apostle sets aside his amanuensis (secretary) to write directly — in large, perhaps awkward script — because the gospel he has been defending is worth this personal emphasis. The God who sends a personal Messenger (Mal 3:1; John 3:16) validates messages through personal investment; Paul's hand-written postscript is a small enactment of this principle.</p>""",
    "12": """<p>Direct: the Judaizers "want to impress people by means of the flesh" and are "trying to avoid being persecuted for the cross of Christ." This is the clearest statement of the social-political motivation behind the circumcision demand: to avoid the social cost of being identified with a crucified criminal. The cross imposes a cost in every social environment; circumcision removes the cost by making the community's identity legible within Jewish religious categories. The direct connection: the cross as the cause of persecution means the cross is the defining, unavoidable claim. To suppress the cross's offense is to evacuate the gospel's power.</p>""",
    "13": """<p>A revelation of God: Paul's observation that "not even those who are circumcised keep the law" exposes the incoherence of the Judaizer position — they cannot themselves fulfill what they demand of others. The self-revelation of failure that the law produces (3:22) applies equally to those who insist on it as the condition for others. This is the NT development of the OT prophetic critique of religious leaders whose practice contradicts their preaching (Isa 58:1-7; Matt 23:3). God requires consistency; the gospel exposes its absence.</p>""",
    "14": """<p>Direct: "May I never boast except in the cross of our Lord Jesus Christ, through which the world has been crucified to me, and I to the world." Paul's sole boast is the cross — the place where all human religious achievement, social status, and cultural identity is relativized and surpassed. "The world has been crucified to me" — the old age, with its systems of value, honor, and religious performance, has been put to death; Paul belongs to the new world inaugurated by the cross. The cross is not merely Paul's salvation but his new cosmology — the event that redefined what is real and what matters. This is the letter's emotional and theological culmination.</p>""",
    "15": """<p>Direct: "what counts is the new creation" (καινὴ κτίσις) — the eschatological category that supersedes both circumcision and uncircumcision. The new creation is the result of Christ's resurrection and Spirit-sending: those united to Christ are "a new creation" (2 Cor 5:17) — not merely renewed versions of the old but participants in the first fruits of the age to come. The concept fulfills OT prophetic anticipation of cosmic renewal (Isa 65:17-25; 66:22), now inaugurated in Christ and to be consummated at his return. The cross and resurrection do not just save individuals; they initiate the new world.</p>""",
    "16": """<p>A theme: "the Israel of God" — likely a designation for the whole believing community, Jewish and Gentile, who follow "this rule" (the new creation as the only thing that matters). The phrase gathers up the entire argument of Galatians: the true Israel is not defined by circumcision or ethnic descent but by belonging to Christ, the seed of Abraham (3:16, 29). "Peace and mercy" is a blessing drawn from the synagogue liturgy (Numbers 6:24-26); Paul applies it to the covenant community redefined in Christ, claiming the inheritance of Israel's own liturgical blessing for those who are in him.</p>""",
    "17": """<p>Direct: "I bear on my body the marks of Jesus" (τὰ στίγματα τοῦ Ἰησοῦ) — Paul's scars from beatings, imprisonments, and stonings (2 Cor 11:23-27) are his credentials, not circumcision. The marks of Jesus are the physical traces of his identification with Christ's suffering — the apostle who shares in the sufferings of Christ (Phil 3:10; Col 1:24) bears in his body the counter-signs to circumcision: not the religious marks of covenant membership but the wounds of gospel service. The passion of Christ leaves its trace on those who carry the cross's message.</p>""",
    "18": """<p>A theme: the closing benediction — "the grace of our Lord Jesus Christ be with your spirit, brothers and sisters" — returns the letter to its theological center. The entire argument of Galatians — against supplementing the gospel with law-observance — is a defense of grace as the sole basis of covenant standing. The final word is grace; the final term of address is "brothers and sisters," restoring the relational warmth despite the letter's urgency. In Christ, the community that has received grace is sustained by grace and stands before God in grace. The "Amen" is the community's affirmation of a reality that holds even when the letter's rebukes sting.</p>"""
  }
}


def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'galatians')
    merge_comm(existing, GALATIANS)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'galatians', existing)
    print('Galatians 4–6 mkt-christ written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
